[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1946},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F04\u002Fexpress-simple-websocket-chatroom\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F04\u002Fexpress-simple-websocket-chatroom\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F04\u002Fexpress-simple-websocket-chatroom\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F04\u002Fexpress-simple-websocket-chatroom\u002F":1921,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F04\u002Fexpress-simple-websocket-chatroom\u002F":1930},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20230504\u002F3177278058\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1905,"date":1906,"description":26,"extension":1907,"lang":1908,"meta":1909,"navigation":178,"path":1910,"readingMinutes":1911,"seo":1912,"standalone":1913,"stem":1914,"tags":1915,"tldr":1918,"updated":1906,"url":1919,"__hash__":1920},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fexpress-simple-websocket-chatroom.md","Building a Simple WebSocket Chatroom with Express","7172780583",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1897},"minimark",[11,19,24,27,31,34,37,41,44,71,74,90,93,97,100,128,147,341,344,501,504,549,552,556,559,584,603,610,768,775,1110,1122,1133,1319,1322,1325,1583,1586,1869,1872,1878,1886,1890,1893],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"WebSocket","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FYVBTBuU.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26],{},"A quick note on building a simple WebSocket chatroom. I'll mainly use Express as the example, with sample code at the end.",[20,28,30],{"id":29},"whats-websocket","What's WebSocket?",[12,32,33],{},"WebSocket is a relatively new network protocol. The biggest difference from HTTP is that WebSocket is full-duplex. What does that mean? With HTTP, every UI action has to first request data from the backend. For example, when adding a record, the frontend tells the backend to add it, then requests the data again. That's one-way communication.",[12,35,36],{},"WebSocket is different from HTTP's one-way model. Once a WebSocket handshake is established, every transfer afterwards is bi-directional. When we add a record, the backend can actively push to the frontend without the frontend asking again. That's bi-directional communication.",[20,38,40],{"id":39},"setting-up-the-project","Setting up the project",[12,42,43],{},"To keep things simple, I'll use the Express generator to scaffold a project:",[45,46,51],"pre",{"className":47,"code":48,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"language-bash shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","express --view=ejs express-websocket\n","bash","",[52,53,54],"code",{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,56,59,63,67],"span",{"class":57,"line":58},"line",1,[55,60,62],{"class":61},"s_sBn","express",[55,64,66],{"class":65},"sCcAr"," --view=ejs",[55,68,70],{"class":69},"sTRMh"," express-websocket\n",[12,72,73],{},"We need a package to handle WebSocket, so install:",[45,75,77],{"className":47,"code":76,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"npm i ws\n",[52,78,79],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,80,81,84,87],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,82,83],{"class":61},"npm",[55,85,86],{"class":69}," i",[55,88,89],{"class":69}," ws\n",[12,91,92],{},"That's the basic setup done. Let's start building.",[20,94,96],{"id":95},"backend-implementation","Backend implementation",[12,98,99],{},"First, the backend. Project structure so far:",[101,102,103,107,110,113,116,119,122,125],"ul",{},[104,105,106],"li",{},"bin",[104,108,109],{},"node_modules",[104,111,112],{},"public",[104,114,115],{},"routes",[104,117,118],{},"views",[104,120,121],{},"app.js",[104,123,124],{},"package.json",[104,126,127],{},"package-lock.json",[12,129,130,131,134,135,138,139,146],{},"Create a folder called ",[52,132,133],{},"websocket"," in the root, and inside it create ",[52,136,137],{},"index.js",". The official ",[140,141,145],"a",{"href":142,"rel":143},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.npmjs.com\u002Fpackage\u002Fws",[144],"nofollow","ws"," docs give a sample: